[***Problem 10. Prompt: Are the booking rates different for February and October for families staying at the resort? Compare the center, spread, shape, and anything unusual.***]{style="color:royalblue;"}

I wrote the code below to compute exact values that will provide insight about the differences between booking rates for February and October for families staying at the resort. The first statistic computed is similar to a t test statistic that compares the difference in means in two groups and determines is the difference is significant or due to natural variability. In this case, we see that there is indeed a difference of about 7.58 dollars being paid for each day of a booking, with October being more expensive than February. This appears to be statistically significant although we can't know for sure without running a test and computing a p value to check for type one or two errors in computing, but it would take someone with more specialized knowledge in hotel and resort operations to know if this is practically significant.

The second statistic listed is the differences in the standard deviations, or the average amount of variability from the calculated mean, between bookings from October compared to bookings from February. Again, an increase of 3.28 dollars from February to October would appear to be statistically significant on the surface before further testing and analysis, but it would take more specialized knowledge of hotel operations to know if this is practically significant.

Lastly, there is an interquartile range calculated for both groups. This is a measurement of how spread out the middle fifty percent of a dataset is. An IQR is typically used to eliminate the effects of outlying data points on sample statistics such as the mean or the standard deviation. When we eliminate the bottom fourth and the top fourth of bookings, we find the difference between October bookings and February bookings at family resorts to be 1.83 dollars. While this is likely to be statistically significant along with the same caveat from above about statistical significant, I would venture the guess that a difference of less than two dollars being paid per booking is not practically significant to a resort, as it is not practically significant for me as a consumer.

```{r}
mean(familyresort %>% filter(arrival_date_month == "October") %>% pull(adr), na.rm = TRUE)-mean(familyresort %>% filter(arrival_date_month == "February") %>% pull(adr), na.rm = TRUE)

sd(familyresort %>% filter(arrival_date_month == "October") %>% pull(adr), na.rm = TRUE)-sd(familyresort %>% filter(arrival_date_month == "February") %>% pull(adr), na.rm = TRUE)

IQR(familyresort %>% filter(arrival_date_month == "October") %>% pull(adr), na.rm = TRUE)-IQR(familyresort %>% filter(arrival_date_month == "February") %>% pull(adr), na.rm = TRUE)
```

